comments:
As with most perovskites, BaPbO$_{3}$ has a number of phase transitions.  The temperature-driven transitions are summarized in (Fu, 1995), (Moussa, 2001), and (Hestor, 2002). We will follow our usual convention and label the phases by Greek letters, increasing with temperature. \begin{itemize} \item The low temperature structure is \href{current_web_home_dir/AB3C_mC20_12_i_ghi_e-001}{monoclinic $\alpha$-BaPbO$_{3}$}. \item At some point above 26\,K (Ritter, 1989) we find \href{current_web_home_dir/AB3C_oI20_74_e_eg_a-001}{orthorhombic $\beta$-BaPbO$_{3}$} (this structure). \item At 548\,K it transforms into the tetragonal $\gamma$-BaPbO$_{3}$ in the \href{current_web_home_dir/A3BC_tI20_140_ah_b_c-002}{$\gamma$-SrZrO$_{3}$ structure}. \item Finally, above 723-725\,K $\delta$-BaPbO$_{3}$ is in the \href{current_web_home_dir/AB3C_cP5_221_a_c_b-001}{cubic perovskite ($E2_{1}$) structure}. \end{itemize} ~ \vspace{-.25in} 
 All of the metallic sites may be alloyed, we have only listed a small number of possibilities. The oxygen sites may be partially filled, or partially replaced by nitrogen or fluorine. 
 (Fu, 1995) gave the structural information in the $Ibmm$ setting of space group \#74.  We used AFLOW to transform this to the standard $Imma$ setting.  This requires change of the axes so that $(x y z) \rightarrow (y z x)$.
